title: Add amd migraphx execution provider to onnx runtime
body:
**Description**: 

This adds an initial execution provider using [MIGraphX](https://github.com/ROCmSoftwarePlatform/AMDMIGraphX) which supports the AMD ROCm stack. 

As a first step, we have hardcoded the operators supported. In the future, we plan to update this to use an API from [MIGraphX](https://github.com/ROCmSoftwarePlatform/AMDMIGraphX) directly.

This also uses the C/C++ API from [MIGraphX](https://github.com/ROCmSoftwarePlatform/AMDMIGraphX), as this will be more stable. As this hasn't been released as part of the ROCm distribution yet we build this version in the dockerfile. In the future we can switch to just pulling down the debian package from ROCm. 

**Motivation and Context**

To support AMD GPUs in onnx runtime and take advantage of MIGraphX's graph optimizations.

title: Disable LNK4199 winml_dll to enable cuda builds
body:
This is needed to suppress linker warnings in winml_dll that complain that no imports are found for the delayloaded library cublas64*.lib.
When --use_cuda is enabled in the pipeline, it sets CMAKE_SHARED_LINKER_FLAGS which affects all targets including winml_dll.
However, there are no cuda imports in winml_dll, and the linkler throws the 4199 warning.
This suppressed the warning to allow winml_dll build with cuda enabled.

title: Merge windowsai (winml layering) into master
body:
This PR is for comment on bringing the newly layered Windows ML components into the master branch for the ONNX runtime for windows.

This is anticipation of a beta release of these bits over the next couple of months. We will include more documentation on how to use , how the layers work, and the relationships of WinML and ORT and DML (which we introduced to master in ORT v1.0) .

Some of the things we have done in this PR:
    - Added a top level directory "/winml"
    - Contributed all of the windows inbox code from the Windows.AI.MachineLearning namespace into that directory . Making it available using the MIT license.
    - Started a layering effort to have the new Windows.AI.MachineLearning.dll consume the onnxruntime.dll c_abi that we introduced in v1.0 .
    - Added an "adapter" module that gets linked into the core onnxruntime.dll. This adapter is private to the WinML component, and provides ABI functionality required for the layering effort. this is not a new public ABI and is not support for developer to call.
    - made the WinML ABI fully available for public developers to call.
    - You can now include both of these DLL's (WinML + ORT) in your projects that want to use the WinML ABI as a redist component.
    - added cmakery for all of this work. There is now a "use_winml" build flag in addition to the "use_dml" build flag
    - added google test unit tests for the newly added WinML ABI. these are under the top level "winml/test" folder.
    - and several other things :)

Enjoy !

title: [LSTM] C# saving internal states for scoring and usage of tensor sequences as inputs
body:
**Describe the bug**
When scoring a previously trained LSTM network it loses its internal states. Basically if the same Tensor is used as input multiple times the output stays the same.

Additionally i'm not sure how to pass a sequence of Tensors as input to the model and if it is supported right now.

**Urgency**
Normal
(i want to use it within my masters thesis as additional possibility to run exported onnx models from matlab)

**System information**
Win 10
ONNX Runtime v 1.1.1 (via NuGet)
Visual Studio 2017 V 15.9.19 (C#)

**To Reproduce**
I have exported a Matlab LSTM Network combined with fully connected layers to onnx. It was trained on PT1 (first order system) behaviour. But if the same input tensor is given multiple times to the model the output value is always the same.
I can gladly provide sample code if needed.
[ONNX_PT1.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4139668/ONNX_PT1.zip)

**Expected behavior**
My goal is to run it in a kind of "real-time" environment to mimic the behaviour of a control system. The trained model behaves like a PT1 element (first oder lag). 
When a sequence of multiple zeros and multiple time steps with the same value are given as input (e.g. 0, 0, 0, 0, 2, 2, 2, 2, ... ) then the output should reach the value of the input, but the network seems to forget it's internal states each time ".Run(inputs)" is called on an InferenceSession.

This issue is closely related to #1659

For testing purposes i would also like to use a sequence of tensors to see if the ONNXRuntime behaviour is the same as in Matlab, but this becomes obsolete for me if the models internal state could be preserved.

Is there an option to keep the internal state or save it after each "Run" and apply it to the InferenceSession before running?

title: Add opset version check
body:
**Description**: 

If the model has a opset version newer than onnxruntime knows,  throw an exception.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

From: @pranavsharma 
Sent: Friday, November 8, 2019 7:32 PM
Subject: Note about opset forward compatibility in ORT.
 
Dwayne from the WinML team apprised me of this issue today afternoon. ORT supports opset 11 in 1.0. Let's say the resize op undergoes a change in behavior in opset 12. The schema would be the same, but the behavior would be different (possibly a spec upgrade happened causing it’s behavior to change). Now if a model that is stamped with opset 12 is inferred by ORT (that implements only opset 11), ORT will use the opset 11 implementation of the op since it registered the op as 11->INF. This doesn’t seem correct because we silently pick the wrong op implementation instead of giving an error. If we clamp our op registration with the opset version we're implementing in the release (in this case opset 11), we will (correctly) throw an error for the unimplemented opset 12 resize op.

This struct would point to the latest API and the old one would be renamed. title: Fix batch mode output for TfIdfVectorizer
body:
**Description**:
For shapes [B][C] TfIdfVectorizer must index weights per row to produce a correct output.
I.e. Weight indexing must restart as we process data in batches (rows)
This also fixes a bug of addressing weights attribute out of range.

**Motivation and Context**
The computed output_size refers to a single row. To date the batch mode was not used so the indexing was always flat and never ran out of a single row which is always equal to the max(index) + 1 and the size of weights. For multiple batches(rows) we must restart weights indexing for every batch.
